    "annotations": [
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION"
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "The immature virion is composed of 180 VP70 subunits with 90 dimeric spikes and displays a T=3 icosahedral symmetry. During maturation, VP70 undergoes a loss of 60 peripentonal spikes, which likely plays an important role in viral infectivity"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "The capsid polyprotein VP90 self-assembles and undergoes a proteolytic cleavage by host caspases to yield the immature VP70 virion"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Self-assembles to form an icosahedral capsid with a T=3 symmetry, about 43 nm in diameter. This forms contains only 30 spikes located on the icosahedral 2-fold axes"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "VP25 and VP27 Forms the spikes at the surface of the virion. This forms contains only 30 spikes located on the icosahedral 2-fold axes. Plays a role in the attachment to target host cell. This attachment induces virion internalization through clathrin-dependent endocytosis"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "VP25 and VP27 Forms the spikes at the surface of the virion. This forms contains only 30 spikes located on the icosahedral 2-fold axes. Plays a role in the attachment to target host cell. This attachment induces virion internalization through clathrin-dependent endocytosis"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "SUBCELLULAR LOCATION",
          "subcellularLocations": [
            {
              "location": {
                "value": "Virion"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "PTM",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Specific enzymatic cleavages by the host yield mature proteins. VP90 acidic C-terminal domain is eliminated from the immature virion by host caspases during viral maturation giving rise to virions composed of VP70. The virus can then dissociate from cellular membranes and exit the cell. Further cleavages by host extracellular proteases occur resulting in the three structural proteins VP34, VP27 and VP25 and conferring infectivity"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "SIMILARITY",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Belongs to the astroviridae capsid polyprotein family"
            }
          ]
        }
